canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe parents of an eight-year-old girl present to the General Practice requesting genetic testing for Huntington disease. The child\u0027s grandmother was recently diagnosed with the condition. The parents are anxious about their daughter\u0027s future risk and want to know if she carries the gene mutation. The child appears healthy with no neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical approach to this genetic testing request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Defer testing until the child can make an autonomous decision","Proceed with testing if it aligns with the child\u0027s best interests","Conduct testing if both parents provide consent","Test immediately to enable early lifestyle modifications","Perform testing to facilitate future planning"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct ethical approach is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edefer testing until the child can make an autonomous decision\u003C/strong\u003E. Since Huntington disease typically presents in adulthood and has no preventive interventions in childhood, testing during childhood provides no medical benefit while potentially causing psychological harm and violating the child\u0027s future autonomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect approaches can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with testing if it aligns with the child\u0027s best interests\u003C/strong\u003E - Testing for adult-onset conditions does not align with a child\u0027s best interests when there are no childhood interventions available\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduct testing if both parents provide consent\u003C/strong\u003E - Parental consent alone is insufficient justification for genetic testing of adult-onset conditions in children\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETest immediately to enable early lifestyle modifications\u003C/strong\u003E - There are no evidence-based lifestyle interventions in childhood that would alter the course of Huntington disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform testing to facilitate future planning\u003C/strong\u003E - The potential benefits of advance planning do not outweigh the child\u0027s right to make autonomous decisions about their genetic information\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenetic testing for adult-onset conditions should be deferred until the child can participate in informed decision-making, unless there are clear medical benefits during childhood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, testing for Huntington disease follows a sequential pattern through generations. The affected parent (in this case, the parent whose mother has Huntington disease) should be tested first, as if they have not inherited the genetic mutation, there is no risk to their child. This sequential approach prevents unnecessary testing and anxiety in subsequent generations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Genetic testing in children should only be performed when there is clear medical benefit during childhood.","Predictive genetic testing for adult-onset conditions should be deferred until the child can make an autonomous decision.","Parents cannot override a competent child\u0027s refusal to undergo genetic testing.","Testing for Huntington disease follows a sequential pattern through generations as inheritance risk depends on parental status."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","Royal College of Pathologists of Australasia. Huntington disease genetic test. Available at: https://www.rcpa.edu.au/Manuals/RCPA-Manual/Pathology-Tests/H/Huntington-disease-genetic-test"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T08:03:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T08:03:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10796"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75886"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"cr